h-jadi-ketua-osis-lho|title=Wah, Isyana Sarasvati Ternyata Pernah Jadi Ketua Osis Lho - Hai|website=hai.grid.id}}</ref>\n* 2007 Chairperson of English Division, Taruna Bakti Problem Solving Contest (Bandung,  Indonesia)\n* 2006\u20132007 Vice President Student Organisation Taruna Bakti Secondary School (Bandung, Indonesia)\n* 2006 Participant 1st International Convention for Youth Leaders, Singapore (RGS-ICYL 2006)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|www.isyanasarasvati.com}}\n*{{Kapanlagi|i|isyana_sarasvati}}\n*[https://www.discogs.com/artist/5756972-Isyana-Sarasvati Isyana Sarasvati discography] on [[Discogs]]\n*[https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/isyana-sarasvati/929562709 Isyana Sarasvati discography] on [[iTunes]]\n*{{Instagram|isyanasarasvati}}\n*{{Twitter|isyanasarasvati}}\n*{{YouTube|channel=UCsNmCa9ubwale8yTpHXJSGA|IsyanaVEVO}}\n\n{{Mnet Asian Music Award for Best Asian Artist}}\n{{The Voice Indonesia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarasvati, Isyana}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Indonesian composers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian female singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian jazz singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Indonesian sopranos]]\n[[Category:Indonesian soul singers]]\n[[Category:Javanese people]]\n[[Category:People from Bandung]]\n[[Category:Anugerah Musik Indonesia winners]]\n[[Category:Mnet Asian Music Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indonesian Muslims]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Women in electronic music]]\n", "name_user": "Ditaap13", "label": "safe", "comment": "Forbes Asia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isyana_Sarasvati"}
{"title_page": "St. Martinus University Faculty of Medicine", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name              = St. Martinus University Faculty of Medicine\n| image_name        = St. Martinus University, Faculty of Medicine logo.png\n| type              = [[Medical School]]\n| president         = Sanjay Sharma\n| location          = Scherpenheuvel, [[Willemstad]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| coor              = {{Coord|12.11186|-68.87880|type:edu_region:CW|display=inline,title}}\n| website           = {{url|http://www.martinus.edu}}\n|language = English}}\n\n'''St. Martinus University Faculty of Medicine''' ('''SMUFOM''') is a [[private university|private]] [[medical school]] located in [[Willemstad]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], which started operating in 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=St. Martinus celebrated its 10th anniversary |url=https://amigoe.com/amigoe-express/84-amigoe-express/166314-st-martinus-celebrated-its-10th-anniversary |work=Amigoe Express |date=15 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309201400/https://amigoe.com/amigoe-express/84-amigoe-express/166314-st-martinus-celebrated-its-10th-anniversary |archivedate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, the school had half the number of students it needed to break even,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ceaser|first1=Mike|date=October 2005|volume=52|issue=10 |title=Sun, Sand, and an M.D.(Caribbean medical schools)|journal=[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]|pages=A55\u2013A60|publisher=The Chronicle of Higher Education Inc. |url= http://business.highbeam.com/434953/article-1G1-147067654/sun-sand-and-md|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140308040311/http://business.highbeam.com/434953/article-1G1-147067654/sun-sand-and-md|url-status= dead|archive-date= 2014-03-08|access-date=2013-02-24}}</ref> and in October 2007, Banco de Caribe announced an auction of the university property. Education of students never halted and the auction never actually manifested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liveincuracao.com/index.php?p=436 |title=The Cura\u00e7ao Islandguide - Yet the end for St. Martinus University |publisher=Liveincuracao.com |accessdate=2013-02-26}}</ref> In 2010, SMU came under the administration of Priyamvada Sharma.<ref>http://www.martinus.edu/welcome-2/history/</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the university became a designated educational institution for the Canada Student Loans Program.<ref>{{cite web |title=List of Designated Educational Institutions - International |url=http://tools.canlearn.ca/cslgs-scpse/cln-cln/reea-mdl/reea-mdl-1-eng.do?nom-name=inter |publisher=Government of Canada, Human Resources and Skills Development Canada, Canada Student Loans Program |accessdate=24 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThird-year medical students do [[Clinical clerkship|clerkships]] at Pontiac General Hospital, in [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]], [[Michigan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20160320/NEWS/303209996/medical-school-ties-aid-pontiac-generals-turnaround|title=Med school ties aid Pontiac hospital's turnaround|website=Crain's Detroit Business|language=en|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>\n\nSt. Martinus University is listed in the [[World Directory of Medical Schools]], and its graduates are eligible to apply for [[Educational Commission for Foreign Medical Graduates|ECFMG]] certification, allowing them to take the [[United States Medical Licensing Examination]] and become licensed to practice medicine in the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.wdoms.org/home/SchoolDetail/F0000044|title=School Detail|website=search.wdoms.org|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref> It is recognized by the [[Medical Council of India]] as a degree-granting university/institution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mciindia.org/CMS/information-desk/for-students-to-study-in-abroad|title=For Students to Study in Abroad {{!}} MCI India|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> It is not accredited by the [[Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and other Health Professions]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caam-hp.org/programs?page=1&category=Medical+School|title=Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and Other Health Professions - http://caam-hp.org|website=caam-hp.org|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> [[Accreditation Commission of Colleges of Medicine]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accredmed.org/accredited-schools/|title=Accredited Schools \u2013 ACCM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> or [[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nvao.net/en/decisions/institutions|title=Decisions and reports|website=www.nvao.net|language=en|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[International medical graduate]]\n* [[List of medical schools in the Caribbean]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.martinus.edu}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St. Martinus University Faculty of Medicine}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Schools of medicine in Cura\u00e7ao]]\n[[Category:Willemstad]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in the Netherlands Antilles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name              = St. Martinus University Faculty of Medicine\n| image_name        = St. Martinus University, Faculty of Medicine logo.png\n| type              = [[Medical School]]\n| president         = Sanjay Sharma\n| location          = Scherpenheuvel, [[Willemstad]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| coor              = {{Coord|12.11186|-68.87880|type:edu_region:CW|display=inline,title}}\n| website           = {{url|http://www.martinus.edu}}\n|language = English}}\n\n'''St. Martinus University Faculty of Medicine''' ('''SMUFOM''') is a [[private university|private]] [[medical school]] located in [[Willemstad]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], which started operating in 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=St. Martinus celebrated its 10th anniversary |url=https://amigoe.com/amigoe-express/84-amigoe-express/166314-st-martinus-celebrated-its-10th-anniversary |work=Amigoe Express |date=15 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309201400/https://amigoe.com/amigoe-express/84-amigoe-express/166314-st-martinus-celebrated-its-10th-anniversary |archivedate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, the school had half the number of students it needed to break even,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ceaser|first1=Mike|date=October 2005|volume=52|issue=10 |title=Sun, Sand, and an M.D.(Caribbean medical schools)|journal=[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]|pages=A55\u2013A60|publisher=The Chronicle of Higher Education Inc. |url= http://business.highbeam.com/434953/article-1G1-147067654/sun-sand-and-md|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140308040311/http://business.highbeam.com/434953/article-1G1-147067654/sun-sand-and-md|url-status= dead|archive-date= 2014-03-08|access-date=2013-02-24}}</ref> and in October 2007, Banco de Caribe announced an auction of the university property. Education of students never halted and the auction never actually manifested.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liveincuracao.com/index.php?p=436 |title=The Cura\u00e7ao Islandguide - Yet the end for St. Martinus University |publisher=Liveincuracao.com |accessdate=2013-02-26}}</ref> In 2010, SMU came under the administration of Priyamvada Sharma.<ref>http://www.martinus.edu/welcome-2/history/</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the university became a designated educational institution for the Canada Student Loans Program.<ref>{{cite web |title=List of Designated Educational Institutions - International |url=http://tools.canlearn.ca/cslgs-scpse/cln-cln/reea-mdl/reea-mdl-1-eng.do?nom-name=inter |publisher=Government of Canada, Human Resources and Skills Development Canada, Canada Student Loans Program |accessdate=24 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThird-year medical students do [[Clinical clerkship|clerkships]] at Pontiac General Hospital, in [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]], [[Michigan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20160320/NEWS/303209996/medical-school-ties-aid-pontiac-generals-turnaround|title=Med school ties aid Pontiac hospital's turnaround|website=Crain's Detroit Business|language=en|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>\n\nSt. Martinus University is listed in the [[World Directory of Medical Schools]], and its graduates are eligible to apply for [[Educational Commission for Foreign Medical Graduates|ECFMG]] certification, allowing them to take the [[United States Medical Licensing Examination]] and become licensed to practice medicine in the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.wdoms.org/home/SchoolDetail/F0000044|title=School Detail|website=search.wdoms.org|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref> It is recognized by the [[Medical Council of India]] as a degree-granting university/institution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mciindia.org/CMS/information-desk/for-students-to-study-in-abroad|title=For Students to Study in Abroad {{!}} MCI India|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> It is not accredited by the [[Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and other Health Professions]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caam-hp.org/programs?page=1&category=Medical+School|title=Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and Other Health Professions - http://caam-hp.org|website=caam-hp.org|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> [[Accreditation Commission of Colleges of Medicine]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accredmed.org/accredited-schools/|title=Accredited Schools \u2013 ACCM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> or [[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nvao.net/en/decisions/institutions|title=Decisions and reports|website=www.nvao.net|language=en|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[International medical graduate]]\n* [[List of medical schools in the Caribbean]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.martinus.edu}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St. Martinus University Faculty of Medicine}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Schools of medicine in Cura\u00e7ao]]\n[[Category:Willemstad]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in the Netherlands Antilles]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Martinus_University_Faculty_of_Medicine"}
{"title_page": "Beverly Duan", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Beverly Duan\n| image              = Beverly Duan.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Beverly Duan at the [[25th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = Beverly Duan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1999|12|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| occupation         = {{Flatlist|\n* Actress\n* musician\n* singer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2002-present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed             = yes\n| background       = solo_singer \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place      = \n| origin           = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date first) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            =  {{Flatlist|\n* [[Pop]]\n* [[R&B]]\n}}\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = {{Flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* piano\n}}\n| years_active     = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [http://www.beverlyduan.com/index.html beverlyduan.com]\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Beverly Duan''' (born December 19, 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2901411/|title=Beverly Duan|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>), is an American actress. Her first appearance on television was as a little girl in commercials on the Los Angeles television station KSCI Channel 18. After appearing in commercials and doing voiceovers for radio stations in Southern California, she received wider recognition for her portrayal of Lulu on the [[Nickelodeon]] television series [[Ni Hao, Kai-Lan|''Ni Hao, Kai-Lan'']], which aired from 2007 until 2011. \n\n== Early life ==\nBeverly Duan was born on December 19, 1999 in Los Angeles, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2901411/bio|title=Beverly Duan|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Duan began receiving classical piano training by age four, performing at  music festivals and competing at conventions. She studied under the statewide Music Teachers\u2019 Association of California music program and passed [[Music examination|music examinations]] in piano for the California Certificate of Merit Level 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beverlyduan.com/about.html|title=About|website=BEVERLY DUAN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>  She attended Fairmont Private School and graduated from [[Troy High School (California)|Troy High School]] in Orange County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fairmontschools.com/2008/02/mable-campus-5th-grader-beverly-duan-lends-her-voice-to-nick-jr-show/|title=Mable Campus 5th Grader Beverly Duan Lends Her Voice to Nick Jr. Show|date=2008-02-20|website=Fairmont Private Schools|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She attended Jin\u2019s Dance Studio, where she was part of the Lyrical Youth Ensemble program, competing all over the United States and internationally.<ref>http://showstopperonline.com/results/results_2010/anaheimII.pdf</ref> She subsequently attended [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]], doing a PhD in economics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economics.ucla.edu/graduate/graduate-profiles/|title=Graduate Profiles|website=UCLA Economics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nDuan was cast in a series of commercials for KSCI LA Channel 18 in 2002 as a little girl in \"Live Long, Be Healthy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beverlyduan.com/about.html|title=About|website=BEVERLY DUAN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She later auditioned for a role in the [[Nickelodeon]] series [[Ni Hao, Kai-Lan|''Ni Hao, Kai-Lan'']], ultimately winning the role of Lulu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2008-03-09-0803060454-story.html|title=HOW 'KAI-LAN' GOT HER GROOVE|last=Register|first=PETER LARSEN; Orange County|website=courant.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> ''Ni Hao, Kai-Lan'' saw Duan portraying a [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] role, requiring her to speak in her native English and learn [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin-Chinese]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2008/02/20/nickelodeons-new-kid-show-has-orange-flavor-page-2/|title=Nickelodeon\u2019s new kid show has Orange flavor{{!}} Page 2|date=2008-02-20|website=Orange County Register|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The series became a hit for the network, propelling Duan to more mainstream success.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hale|first=Mike|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/07/arts/television/07hale.html|title=A Pint-Size Peacemaker With a Lot to Teach|date=2008-02-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The series received numerous awards nominations, including one for the [[Daytime Emmy Award|Daytime Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Ni Hao, Kai-Lan - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0934701/awards|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Duan recorded part of the opening theme song for the series.<ref>{{Citation|title=\"Ni Hao, Kai-Lan\" Happy Chinese New Year! (TV Episode 2008) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1409335/fullcredits|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Duan later recorded the holiday song in the episode \"Happy Chinese New Year\".<ref>{{Citation|title=\"Ni Hao, Kai-Lan\" Happy Chinese New Year! (TV Episode 2008) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1409335/fullcredits|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020, Duan released a cover of \"[[Hero (Mariah Carey song)|Hero]]\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Beverly Duan - Hero (Official Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CrgGFfRu9F8|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDuan was born and raised in [[California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beverlyduan.com/about.html|title=About|website=BEVERLY DUAN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Television and film roles\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2007-2011\n|''[[Ni Hao, Kai-Lan]]''\n|Lulu\n|Main voice role\n|}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American actresses]]\n[[Category:American people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Beverly Duan\n| image              = Beverly Duan.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Beverly Duan at the [[25th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = Beverly Duan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1999|12|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| occupation         = {{Flatlist|\n* Actress\n* musician\n* singer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2002-present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed             = yes\n| background       = solo_singer \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place      = \n| origin           = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date first) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            =  {{Flatlist|\n* [[Pop]]\n* [[R&B]]\n}}\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = {{Flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* piano\n}}\n| years_active     = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [http://www.beverlyduan.com/index.html beverlyduan.com]\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Beverly Duan''' (born December 19, 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2901411/|title=Beverly Duan|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>), is an American actress. Her first appearance on television was as a little girl in commercials on the Los Angeles television station KSCI Channel 18. After appearing in commercials and doing voiceovers for radio stations in Southern California, she received wider recognition for her portrayal of Lulu on the [[Nickelodeon]] television series [[Ni Hao, Kai-Lan|''Ni Hao, Kai-Lan'']], which aired from 2007 until 2011. \n\n== Early life ==\nBeverly Duan was born on December 19, 1999 in Los Angeles, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2901411/bio|title=Beverly Duan|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Duan began receiving classical piano training by age four, performing at  music festivals and competing at conventions. She studied under the statewide Music Teachers\u2019 Association of California music program and passed [[Music examination|music examinations]] in piano for the California Certificate of Merit Level 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beverlyduan.com/about.html|title=About|website=BEVERLY DUAN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>  She attended Fairmont Private School and graduated from [[Troy High School (California)|Troy High School]] in Orange County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fairmontschools.com/2008/02/mable-campus-5th-grader-beverly-duan-lends-her-voice-to-nick-jr-show/|title=Mable Campus 5th Grader Beverly Duan Lends Her Voice to Nick Jr. Show|date=2008-02-20|website=Fairmont Private Schools|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She attended Jin\u2019s Dance Studio, where she was part of the Lyrical Youth Ensemble program, competing all over the United States and internationally.<ref>http://showstopperonline.com/results/results_2010/anaheimII.pdf</ref> She subsequently attended [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]], doing a PhD in economics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economics.ucla.edu/graduate/graduate-profiles/|title=Graduate Profiles|website=UCLA Economics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nDuan was cast in a series of commercials for KSCI LA Channel 18 in 2002 as a little girl in \"Live Long, Be Healthy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beverlyduan.com/about.html|title=About|website=BEVERLY DUAN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She later auditioned for a role in the [[Nickelodeon]] series [[Ni Hao, Kai-Lan|''Ni Hao, Kai-Lan'']], ultimately winning the role of Lulu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2008-03-09-0803060454-story.html|title=HOW 'KAI-LAN' GOT HER GROOVE|last=Register|first=PETER LARSEN; Orange County|website=courant.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> ''Ni Hao, Kai-Lan'' saw Duan portraying a [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] role, requiring her to speak in her native English and learn [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin-Chinese]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2008/02/20/nickelodeons-new-kid-show-has-orange-flavor-page-2/|title=Nickelodeon\u2019s new kid show has Orange flavor{{!}} Page 2|date=2008-02-20|website=Orange County Register|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The series became a hit for the network, propelling Duan to more mainstream success.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hale|first=Mike|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/07/arts/television/07hale.html|title=A Pint-Size Peacemaker With a Lot to Teach|date=2008-02-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The series received numerous awards nominations, including one for the [[Daytime Emmy Award|Daytime Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Ni Hao, Kai-Lan - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0934701/awards|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Duan recorded part of the opening theme song for the series.<ref>{{Citation|title=\"Ni Hao, Kai-Lan\" Happy Chinese New Year! (TV Episode 2008) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1409335/fullcredits|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Duan later recorded the holiday song in the episode \"Happy Chinese New Year\".<ref>{{Citation|title=\"Ni Hao, Kai-Lan\" Happy Chinese New Year! (TV Episode 2008) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1409335/fullcredits|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDuan was born and raised in [[California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beverlyduan.com/about.html|title=About|website=BEVERLY DUAN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Television and film roles\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2007-2011\n|''[[Ni Hao, Kai-Lan]]''\n|Lulu\n|Main voice role\n|}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American actresses]]\n[[Category:American people]]\n", "name_user": "MIA5112", "label": "safe", "comment": "cover of Hero", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beverly_Duan"}
{"title_page": "Saxion University of Applied Sciences", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name         = Saxion University of Applied Sciences\n|native_name  = Saxion Hogescholen\n|image        = Saxion University of Applied Sciences logo.svg\n|motto        = Living Technology\n|established  = 1998\n|type         = [[Hogeschool|University of applied sciences]]\n|students     = +27.000\n|website      = {{URL|saxion.edu}}\n|staff        = 2.825\n|location     = [[Enschede]], [[Deventer]], and [[Apeldoorn]], Netherlands\n|colors       = \n|affiliations = \n}}\n\n'''Saxion University of Applied Sciences''' is a Dutch vocational university with three campuses in the eastern [[Netherlands]]. It provides more than 100 courses in study fields as [[finance]], [[law]], [[engineering]], [[hospitality]], [[business]], [[Information technology|IT]], [[broadcasting]] and [[digital media]]. With over 27,000 students, it is one of the largest institutions of higher education in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saxion.edu/site/about-saxion/about-saxion|title=Saxion University of Applied Sciences|website=www.saxion.edu}}</ref>\n\nSaxion offers bachelor & master education and research focused on '''Living Technology'''.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Saxion enschede.jpg|alt=Saxion Enschede|thumb|Saxion University of Applied Sciences in [[Enschede]]]]\nThe roots of Saxion University can be traced back to the 1875. A merger of two educational institutions, the Hogeschool Enschede and Hogeschool IJselland, in 1998 paved the way for Saxion University in its present form. This merger enabled Saxion to build further on its strong position in Dutch higher education and since then Saxion University has come to be recognised as an important center of expertise at regional, national and international level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saxion.edu/about-saxion/our-organisation|title=Saxion University of Applied Sciences|website=www.saxion.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Academies ==\nSaxion University of Applied Sciences consists of eleven academies, each representing a different field of specialization and study courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saxion.nl/over/organisatie/academies/|title=Academies - Hogeschool Saxion|first=|last=Saxion|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n*School of Business, Building & Technology (BBT)\n*School of Governance, Law & Urban Development (ABRR)\n*School of [[Digital media|Creative Technology]] (ACT)\n*School of Finance & Accounting (FEM)\n*School of Health (AGZ)\n*Hospitality [[Business school|Business School]] (HBS)\n*School of Life Science, Engineering & Design (LED)\n*School of [[Marketing]] & [[Management|International Management]] (MIM)\n*School of [[Applied psychology|Applied Psychology]] and (International) Human Resources Management (AMA)\n*School of Social Work (AMM)\n*School of Education (APO)[[File:Saxion Deventer 2012.jpg|alt=Saxion Deventer|thumb|Saxion University of Applied Sciences in [[Deventer]]]]\n*International Business School (IBS)\n\n== International students ==\nThe university has more than 27,000 students over the three campuses, with more than 3,500 international students from 89 different nationalities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saxion.edu/about-saxion|title=Saxion University of Applied Sciences|website=saxion.edu|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref> The number of students has been growing ever since the founding of the university in 1998.\n\nSaxion helps students build their international future offering support not only from an academic point of view but also in terms of one's personal development. After their graduation students can apply for the Connect Programme, which offers talented graduates trainings, workshops and Dutch lessons free of charge.\n\nIn the end of 2016 Saxion launched the platform IntoSaxion<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://intosaxion.nl/en|title=IntoSaxion|last=|first=|date=|website=intosaxion.nl|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref> to support prospective students getting in touch with other Saxion students and experiencing what it's like to study in the Netherlands.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*https://ibs.saxion.nl\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Dutch Vocational Universities}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vocational universities in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Apeldoorn]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Deventer]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Enschede]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Gelderland]]\n[[Category:Education in Overijssel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name         = Saxion University of Applied Sciences\n|native_name  = Saxion Hogescholen\n|image        = Saxion University of Applied Sciences logo.svg\n|motto        = Living Technology\n|established  = 1998\n|type         = [[Hogeschool|University of applied sciences]]\n|students     = +27.000\n|website      = {{URL|saxion.edu}}\n|staff        = 2.825\n|location     = [[Enschede]], [[Deventer]], and [[Apeldoorn]], Netherlands\n|colors       = \n|affiliations = \n}}\n\n'''Saxion University of Applied Sciences''' is a Dutch vocational university with three campuses in the eastern [[Netherlands]]. It provides more than 100 courses in study fields as [[finance]], [[law]], [[engineering]], [[hospitality]], [[business]], [[Information technology|IT]], [[broadcasting]] and [[digital media]]. With over 27,000 students, it is one of the largest institutions of higher education in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saxion.edu/site/about-saxion/about-saxion|title=Saxion University of Applied Sciences|website=www.saxion.edu}}</ref>\n\nSaxion offers bachelor & master education and research focused on '''Living Technology'''.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Saxion enschede.jpg|alt=Saxion Enschede|thumb|Saxion University of Applied Sciences in [[Enschede]]]]\nThe roots of Saxion University can be traced back to the 1875. A merger of two educational institutions, the Hogeschool Enschede and Hogeschool IJselland, in 1998 paved the way for Saxion University in its present form. This merger enabled Saxion to build further on its strong position in Dutch higher education and since then Saxion University has come to be recognised as an important center of expertise at regional, national and international level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saxion.edu/about-saxion/our-organisation|title=Saxion University of Applied Sciences|website=www.saxion.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Academies ==\nSaxion University of Applied Sciences consists of eleven academies, each representing a different field of specialization and study courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saxion.nl/over/organisatie/academies/|title=Academies - Hogeschool Saxion|first=|last=Saxion|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n*School of Business, Building & Technology (BBT)\n*School of Governance, Law & Urban Development (ABRR)\n*School of [[Digital media|Creative Technology]] (ACT)\n*School of Finance & Accounting (FEM)\n*School of Health (AGZ)\n*Hospitality [[Business school|Business School]] (HBS)\n*School of Life Science, Engineering & Design (LED)\n*School of [[Marketing]] & [[Management|International Management]] (MIM)\n*School of [[Applied psychology|Applied Psychology]] and (International) Human Resources Management (AMA)\n*School of Social Work (AMM)\n*School of Education (APO)[[File:Saxion Deventer 2012.jpg|alt=Saxion Deventer|thumb|Saxion University of Applied Sciences in [[Deventer]]]]\n*International Business School (IBS)\n\n== International students ==\nThe university has more than 27,000 students over the three campuses, with more than 3,500 international students from 89 different nationalities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saxion.edu/about-saxion|title=Saxion University of Applied Sciences|website=saxion.edu|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref> The number of students has been growing ever since the founding of the university in 1998.\n\nSaxion helps students build their international future offering support not only from an academic point of view but also in terms of one's personal development. After their graduation students can apply for the Connect Programme, which offers talented graduates trainings, workshops and Dutch lessons free of charge.\n\nIn the end of 2016 Saxion launched the platform IntoSaxion<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://intosaxion.nl/en|title=IntoSaxion|last=|first=|date=|website=intosaxion.nl|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref> to support prospective students getting in touch with other Saxion students and experiencing what it's like to study in the Netherlands.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*https://ibs.saxion.nl\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Dutch Vocational Universities}}\n\n[[Category:Vocational universities in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Apeldoorn]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Deventer]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Enschede]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Gelderland]]\n[[Category:Education in Overijssel]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxion_University_of_Applied_Sciences"}
