ons|2014]]<br />{{small|unified}}\n|{{composition bar|6|22|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|386|906|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|80|204|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|538|2137|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|1794|7836|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|[[Ma Ying-jeou]]\n|-\n![[2010 Taiwanese local elections|2010]]<br />{{small|municipalities only}}\n|{{composition bar|3|5|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|130|314|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{composition bar|1195|3757|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|[[Ma Ying-jeou]]\n|-\n![[2009 Taiwanese local elections|2009]]\n|{{composition bar|12|17|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|289|587|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|121|211|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Ma Ying-jeou]]\n|-\n![[2006 Taiwanese local elections|2006]]<br />{{small|municipalities only}}\n|{{composition bar|1|2|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|41|96|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Ma Ying-jeou]]\n|-\n![[2005 Taiwanese local elections|2005]]\n|{{composition bar|14|23|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|408|901|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|173|319|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Ma Ying-jeou]]\n|-\n![[2002 Taiwanese local elections|2002]]<br />{{small|municipalities only}}\n|{{composition bar|1|2|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|32|96|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Lien Chan]]\n|-\n![[2001 Taiwanese local elections|2001]]\n|{{composition bar|9|23|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|382|897|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|195|319|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Lien Chan]]\n|-\n![[1998 Taiwanese municipal elections|1998]]<br />{{small|municipalities only}}\n|{{composition bar|1|2|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|48|96|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Lee Teng-hui]]\n|-\n![[1997 Taiwanese local elections|1997]]\n|{{composition bar|8|23|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|522|886|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|236|319|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Lee Teng-hui]]\n|-\n![[1994 Taiwanese municipal elections|1994]]<br />{{small|province-level only}}\n|{{composition bar|2|3|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{composition bar|91|175|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n|[[Lee Teng-hui]]\n|}\n\n=== National Assembly elections ===\n{|class=wikitable\n!Election\n!Total seats won\n!Total votes\n!Share of votes\n!Changes\n!Party leader\n!Status\n!President\n|-\n![[2005 Taiwan National Assembly election|2005]]\n|{{composition bar|117|300|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|1,508,384\n|38.92%\n|{{decrease}} 66 seats\n|[[Lien Chan]]\n|{{partial|Plurality}}\n|\n|-\n![[1991 Taiwan National Assembly election|1991]]\n|{{composition bar|254|325|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|6,053,366\n|69.1%\n|{{increase}} 186 seats\n|[[Lee Teng-hui]]\n|{{yes|Majority}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lee Teng-hui]] {{KMT/logo}}\n|-\n![[1996 Taiwan National Assembly election|1996]]\n|{{composition bar|183|334|hex={{Kuomintang/meta/color}}}}\n|5,180,829\n|49.7%\n|{{decrease}} 71 seats\n|[[Lee Teng-hui]]\n|{{yes|Majority}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Conservatism|Taiwan|China|Politics}}\n* [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of China]]\n* [[February 28 Incident]]\n* [[Campaign at the China\u2013Burma border]]\n* [[Chinese nationalism]]\n* [[Conservatism in Taiwan]]\n* [[Elections in Taiwan]]\n* [[Index of Taiwan-related articles]]\n* [[History of the Kuomintang cultural policy]]\n* [[History of the Republic of China]]\n* [[Joseph Stilwell#Disagreements with Chiang and the Allies|Joseph Stilwell]]\n* [[KMT retreat to Taiwan in 1949]]\n* [[Kuomintang Islamic insurgency in China (1950\u201358)]]\n* [[Military of the Republic of China]]\n* [[National Revolutionary Army]]\n* [[Nationalist government]]\n* [[New Kuomintang Alliance]]\n* [[Political status of Taiwan]]\n* [[Politics of the Republic of China]]\n* [[Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang]]\n* [[Outline of Taiwan]]\n* [[Whampoa Military Academy]]\n* [[White Terror (Taiwan)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n=== Words in native languages ===\n{{notelist-ur}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first2=Janet |last2=Lloyd |last1=Bergere |first1=Marie-Claire |title=Sun Yat-sen |year=2000 |publisher=Stanford University Press |location=Stanford, California |isbn=978-0-8047-4011-1 |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/sunyatsen00berg }}\n* {{cite book |last=Strand|first=David |editor1-last=Goldman|editor1-first=Merle |editor2-last=Perry |editor2-first=Elizabeth |editor2-link=Elizabeth J. Perry |title=Changing Meanings of Citizenship in Modern China |chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YF-ftHbw59sC&pg=PA389 |year=2002 |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |isbn=978-0-674-00766-6 |chapter = Chapter 2: Citizens in the Audience and at the Podium |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Roy |first=Denny |title=Taiwan: A Political History |url=https://archive.org/details/taiwan00denn |url-access=registration |year=2003 |publisher=Cornell University Press |location=Ithaca, New York |isbn=978-0-8014-8805-4 |ref=harv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* John F. Copper. ''The KMT Returns to Power: Elections in Taiwan, 2008 to 2012'' (Lexington Books; 2013) 251 pages; A study of how Taiwan's Nationalist Party regained power after losing in 2000.\n* Chris Taylor, \"Taiwan's Seismic shift,\" ''Asian Wall Street Journal'', 4 February 2004 (not available online).\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links}}\n* [http://www.kmt.org.tw/ Kuomintang Official Website] {{in lang|zh}}\n** [http://www.kmt.org.tw/english/page.aspx?type=article&mnum=111 Kuomintang News Network]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091028051800/http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761563041/Kuomintang.html The History of Kuomintang] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20091028051800/http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761563041/Kuomintang.html Archived] 31 October 2009)\n\n{{Chinese Civil War}}\n{{Cold War}}\n{{International Democrat Union}}\n{{KMTleaders}}\n{{Taiwanese political parties}}\n{{Warlord era}}\n{{Chinese Nationalist Party}}\n{{Taiwan topics}}\n{{China topics}}\n\n[[Category:1912 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:History of China]]\n[[Category:History of the Republic of China]]\n[[Category:History of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:International Democrat Union member parties]]\n[[Category:Kuomintang| ]]\n[[Category:Liberal conservative parties]]\n[[Category:National conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Nationalist parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Taipei]]\n[[Category:Parties of one-party systems]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1912]]\n[[Category:Political parties in the Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Republic of China (1912\u20131949)]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist parties]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the party in the Republic of China (Taiwan)|the political party currently active in the People's Republic of China|Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang}}\n{{Redirect|KMT}}\n{{short description|Political party in the Republic of China (Taiwan)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n<!--- Traditional Chinese are shown, with the [[Indo-European languages|applicable]] transliterations and that complies with the Wikipedia policy about Simplified and Traditional Chinese.\nNote 2: PLEASE, DO NOT ERASE THE WIKTIONARY LINKS. Inside the linguistics box, each character has an internal link to the wiki sister project (wiktionary) which provides for a definition of each of the applicable characters.\nNote 3: PLEASE, GO TO DISCUSSION AND EXPRESS YOUR POV ABOUT THE POSITION OF THE LINGUISTICS BOX.\nDO NOT EDIT THE SECTION ABOVE WITHOUT DISCUSSION ON THE TALK PAGE. --->\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Kuomintang{{efn native lang|tw|name=word1\n  |t=\u4e2d\u570b\u570b\u6c11\u9ee8\n  |p=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 Gu\u00f3m\u00ednd\u01ceng\n  |m=Tiong-kok Kok-b\u00een-t\u00f3ng\n  |s=}}\n| colorcode = {{Kuomintang/meta/color}}\n| logo = Emblem of the Kuomintang.svg\n| logo_size = 125px\n| abbreviation = KMT\n| chairman = [[Johnny Chiang|Johnny Chiang Chi-chen]]\n| secretary_general = [[Tseng Ming-chung]] <small>(acting)\n| foundation = {{start date and age|df=y|1919|10|10}}\n| predecessor = {{unbulleted list\n  |[[Revive China Society]] (1894)\n  |[[Tongmenghui]] (1905)\n  |Nationalist Party (1912)\n  |Chinese Revolutionary Party (1914)}}\n| headquarters = 232\u2013234 Sec 2 Bade Rd, [[Zhongshan District, Taipei|Zhongshan District]], Taipei, [[Free area of the Republic of China|ROC]]<br/>10492<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmt.org.tw/english/index.aspx|title=Kuomintang Official Website|publisher=Kuomintang|accessdate=13 September 2011}}</ref>\n| newspaper = {{unbulleted list\n  |[http://www.cntimes.info/ ''Central Daily News'']\n  |{{nowrap|''Kuomintang News Network''}}}}\n| think_tank = [http://www.npf.org.tw/ National Policy Foundation]\n| youth_wing = [[Kuomintang Youth League]]\n |membership_year = 2020\n |membership    = 345,971<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202003075010.aspx|title=\u6c5f\u555f\u81e3\u58d3\u5012\u6027\u52dd\u51fa \u6210\u6700\u5e74\u8f15\u570b\u6c11\u9ee8\u4e3b\u5e2d - \u4e2d\u592e\u793eCNA|date=|accessdate=2020-03-07}}\n</ref>\n| ideology = {{unbulleted list|class=nowrap\n  |[[Three Principles of the People]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmt.org.tw/p/blog-page_3.html|script-title=zh:\u653f\u7b56\u7db1\u9818|publisher=Kmt.org.tw|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref><re